The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Centre notifies depreciation rate cuts

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 New Delhi, March 2: The government today issued a notification reducing the rate of depreciation on machinery and plant from 25 per cent to 15 per cent, furniture and fittings from 15 per cent to 10 per cent, motor cars (not used in a business of running them on hire) from 20 per cent to 15 per cent.

 On motor buses, motor lorries and motor taxis used in a business of running them on hire the rate has been slashed from 40 per cent to 30 per cent.

 The depreciation rates for moulds used in rubber and plastic goods factories were reduced from 40 per cent to 30 per cent, machinery and plant used in semi-conductor industry from 40 per cent to 30 per cent, gas cylinders, including valves and regulators, from 80 per cent to 60 per cent and direct fire glass melting furnaces from 80 to 60 per cent.

 On mineral oil companies, the rate has been cut from 80 per cent to 60 per cent and on shipping firms from 25 per cent to 20 per cent.

 The notification issued by the Central Board of Direct Taxes amending the Income-tax Rules, 1962 with a view to rationalising the rates of depreciation admissible for block of assets as per the provisions of the income-tax rules is also available on the website of the finance ministry (finmin.nic.in).




